param.name: NoteText
param.value:
1. Are you willing to be contacted by phone by the nightime observer? If so, please include a note with your preferred contact information.
2. Two imaging templates are provided. The "Sparse Field" template uses 15" offsets with no offsets to sky. The "Crowded Field / Extended Object" template uses 10" offsets on-source and then offsets 5 arcminutes to a blank field where it does unguided 30" offsets. The size and direction of the initial offset may need to be modified to insure that the sky dithers are in a clear and uncrowded region.
3. If any objects may saturate with the chosen exposure time please include a note stating whether this is okay, or whether the observer should reduce the exposure time. Please have in mind that the background can vary strongly depending on the conditions (e.g. due to high WV or thermal emission from the atmosphere in the K-band, or OH emission in the J band).
4. If there are unusual observing constraints (delivered FWHM/cloud cover/airmass/hour angle/scheduling) please include a note with the details.
5. If this a non-sidereal target please include a note with the details.
6. If any observations are to be taken with the Cass rotator fixed please include a note with the title "CR FIXED".
7. If the automatic guide star selection failed for any observation please include a note and talk with your contact scientist to validate any manually-selected guide stars.
8. At the NIR wavelength range, for a given brightness we usually face an uncertainty of factor 2-3 in BG plus target level per pixel just within any single bin of conditions CC/IQ/BG/WV. For a single CDS read ("bright target" mode) the science target peak signal should not surpass 22k ADUs. For 4 and 8 reads ("medium" and "faint") should not surpass 88k and 172k ADUs.
9. Please have in mind that it is advisable to spend more time off-telescope choosing the standards and avoid the situation of saturating even for the minimum possible exposure time. In that case the Observer will have to spend observing time choosing a different standard (or telluric in the case of spectroscopy).
10. Don't forget to include daytime imaging flats.
11. Darks are now taken weekly.
12. Feel free to include a note with any any special advice for the observer.

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
When choosing the detector readout modes or changing the exposure times, please have in mind:
Single CDS read (Bright Object Mode) can be used for any exposure time (Minimum possible 2 seconds). In imaging applications, the FLAMINGOS-2 detector is always sky-noise limited using single reads. Calibrations (imaging/spectroscopy flats and arcs) are all taken with Bright Object mode.
4 reads (Medium Object Mode) requires exposure times longer than 21 seconds.
8 reads (Faint Object Mode) requires exposure times longer than 85 seconds.
4 and 8 read modes are only recommended for spectroscopy observations.
When modifying the exposure times set at the library example sequences, or on-the-fly while observing, please check that the appropriate readout mode is set in order to avoid time-out errors when the instrument sequencer tries a wrong configuration.

param.name: NoteText
param.value: Instead of dithering after each image is taken, it is recommended to take a few images on the same dithering position before moving to the next dithering position or the sky postion. The sky background variation will still be minimum and telescope time will be saved.

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
Imaging flats are daytime calibrations and do not need to be taken at the same position of the target. The main purpose of them is to correct for pixel to pixel response variations, therefore a smooth illumination is all that is needed (and what GCAL provides). The smooth surface is later normalized to get the relative response of the pixels.
Imaging transmission sky flats can be created from the science observations themselves (the sky background is high enough to allow the dithered positions to be used for making the flat). Please note that the optics transmission per design should vary smoothly less than 0.5% within the central three arcminutes. We do not recommend to use K-band flatfields because there is non-negligible variable thermal emission background from the telescope and the OIWFS base mechanism. The H-band sky flat can be succesfully applied to correct transmission across the FOV in the K-band.
J and H band lamp flats have versions with GCAL shutter open and closed, in order to allow for scattering subtraction in case they are used for correcting the radial transmission variation. K band lamp flats are taken with GCAL shutter closed, as the thermal contribution from the environment is too high to get a non-saturated flat.

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
The baseline imaging calibrations, not charged, are 6 flats per filter, and 6 shutter-closed flats to subtract background illumination.
More imaging flats from the same epoch will usually be available through the science archive.
Darks are obtained on a weekly basis as non-charged instrument calibrations. There is no need to add them in the program sequences.
20200501, RD

1. Are you willing to be contacted by phone by the nightime observer? If so, please include a note with your preferred contact information.
2. Every Flamingos2 long-slit observation must have an associated acqusition. See the F2 spectroscopy web page fore more details: http://www.gemini.edu/sciops/instruments/flamingos2/spectroscopy
3. Very bright targets (H < 12) may be easily acquired without sky subtraction. For all other targets we recommend using the H>12 acquisition template which includes a sky offset.
4. Very faint targets (H>20) must be acquired using a blind offset from a nearby reference star.
5. If the target H-band magnitude was included in the Phase-I definition, the OT will provide the appropriate acquisition templates. Examples of all acquisition types may be copied from the Flamingos2 OT library.
6. Two long-slit spectroscopy templates are provided. The "Sparse Field" template uses an ABBA pattern with 10" offsets along the slit. The "Extended Object" template uses a 10" ABBA pattern interspersed with 5 arcminute offsets to a clear field which is observed unguided. The size and direction of the sky offset may need to be modified to ensure that the sky dithers are in a clear and uncrowded region.
7. Include TWO Telluric standard observations; one which is (observation time / 2) in RA before and another which is (observation time / 2) after the science target with similar Declination. Unless requested, only one telluric will be observed per 2 hours of science spectra.
8. Please have in mind that it is advisable to spend more time off-telescope choosing the standards and avoid the situation of saturating even for the minimum possible exposure time. In that case the Observer will have to spend observing time choosing a different standard (or telluric in the case of spectroscopy).
9. At the NIR wavelength range, for a given brightness we usually face an uncertainty of factor 2-3 in BG plus target level per pixel just within any single bin of conditions CC/IQ/BG/WV. For a single CDS read ("bright target" mode) the science target peak signal should not surpass 22k ADUs. For 4 and 8 reads ("medium" and "faint") should not surpass 88k and 172k ADUs.
10. Please attach finder charts via the OT "File Attachment" tab.
11. Darks are now taken weekly.
12. Feel free to include a note with any any special advice for the observer.

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
The standard strategy for point like or compact objects involves the use of ABBA offsets. In this template, a Repeat iterator contains the ABBA offsets, in this way the offset strategy is conserved in each Repeat iteration (e.g. ABBAABBAABBA).
However, different approaches are possible: some PI's observing bright objects want to have the repeat a few times in each offset, in order to save overhead time (i.e. AAABBBAAABBB). After a couple of minutes of short spectral exposures in the same node, the telescope is moved to next node. Other strategies involve using ABABABAB offsets because the sky contribution is modeled and uniform time sampling is needed.
Any offset strategy must take into account that the sky emission lines can vary significatively in scales of 2 to 5 minutes.

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
The baseline spectroscopic calibrations, charged to the partner, include:
a) 5 flats and 1 arc planned per 2 hours of observation, embedded in the science sequence.
b) A telluric standard observation per 2 hours of observation (two options should be included, before and after the science target).
c) For K-long and HK observations, one shutter closed flat is obtained in order to substract the thermal background from the arcs.
Darks are obtained on a weekly basis as non-charged instrument calibrations. There is no need to add them in the program sequences.
20200501, RD

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
1. Are you willing to be contacted by phone by the nightime observer? If so, please include a note with your preferred contact information.
2. Every Flamingos2 MOS observation must have an associated acqusition. See the F2 spectroscopy web page fore more details: http://www.gemini.edu/sciops/instruments/flamingos2/spectroscopy
3. Three MOS spectroscopy templates are provided. The "Sparse Field" template uses an ABBA pattern with 1.2" offsets along the slit. Note that the slit lenght must be 5" or longer. The "Crowded field or Extended Object" template uses an ABBA pattern with the B nod located 5 arcminute on a clear field which is observed unguided. The size and direction of the sky offset may need to be modified to ensure that the sky dithers are in a clear and uncrowded region. The "Sparse Field - K-band" has a calibration sequence that includes a shutter closed (non-illuminated) 'flat' in order to subtract the thermal background from the arc.
4. The recommended slit lenght is no less than 5 arcsec if nodding is performed on the slit. The separation between slits has to be no less than 0.72".
5. If your target is extended or in a crowded field, you may need to change the size of the sky offsets to obtain good sky subtraction.
6. Include TWO Telluric standard observations; one which is (observation time / 2) in RA before and another which is (observation time / 2) after the science target with similar Declination. Unless requested, only one telluric each two hours of observation will be observed. The telluric standard spectroscopy includes six nodding positions, up to one arcmin away from the FOV center.
7. Please have in mind that it is advisable to spend more time off-telescope choosing the standards and avoid the situation of saturating even for the minimum possible exposure time. In that case the Observer will have to spend observing time choosing a different standard (or telluric in the case of spectroscopy).
8. At the NIR wavelength range, for a given brightness we usually face an uncertainty of factor 2-3 in BG plus target level per pixel just within any single bin of conditions CC/IQ/BG/WV. For a single CDS read ("bright target" mode) the science target peak signal should not surpass 22k ADUs. For 4 and 8 reads ("medium" and "faint") should not surpass 88k and 172k ADUs.
9. Darks are now taken weekly.
10. Please attach the F2 field image or pseudoimage and the corresponding object definition file (ODF) via the OT "File Attachment" tab.
11. Feel free to include a note with any any special advice for the observer.

Slits can be shorter than 5 arcsec only in the case of large offsets to take sky crowded fields and extended objects.
